## Critical Rules for Finding Numbers Based on Division

### Rule: Number = (Divisor × Quotient) + Remainder

This rule allows us to reconstruct the original number when given the divisor, quotient, and remainder.

#### Example Problems:

| Problem | Given Values | Solution |
|--------|--------------|----------|
| Example 10 | Least 5-digit number divisible by 632 | 10000 ÷ 632 → Remainder = 520; Required Number = 10000 + (632 - 520) = 10112 |
| Example 11 | Greatest 5-digit number divisible by 463 | 99999 ÷ 463 → Remainder = 454; Required Number = 99999 - 454 = 99545 |
| Example 12 | Nearest number to 13700 divisible by 235 | 13700 ÷ 235 → Remainder = 70; Required Number = 13700 - 70 = 13630 |

---

## Divisibility Tests

Here's a concise list of rules to determine whether a number is divisible by another without performing actual division.

| Divisor | Divisibility Rule | Example |
|--------|-------------------|---------|
| 2 | Last digit is 0 or even | 12, 102, 134 |
| 3 | Sum of digits is divisible by 3 | 3792 (3+7+9+2=21) |
| 4 | Last two digits form a number divisible by 4 | 2616 (last two digits = 16) |
| 5 | Last digit is 0 or 5 | 13520, 7805 |
| 6 | Even number and sum of digits is divisible by 3 | 4518 (even & sum = 18) |
| 7 | Double the last digit and subtract from remaining

